It has been stated above that Cicero was a novus homo, and as such would naturally belong to the democratic party. From the date of his consulship. however, he seems to have attached himself to the optimates, or aristocratic party, and accordingly at the outbreak of the civil war in 49 B.c., after some hesitation, he joined Pompey, but sub- sequently, after the battle of Pharsalia in 48 B.c., he was ‘reconciled to Caesar. After the death of Caesar, 44 Bo, an open rupture ensued between him and Antony, and Cicero gave vent to his anger and indignation 111 the famous ‘ Philippic Orations‚' fourteen specches, the finest and most renowned of which is the second. From the beginning of 43 B.o. until the end of April Cicero was, in the height os his glory, but before the end of that year, in the pro- scription that followed upon the formation of the trium- vir-ate, Cicero‘s name was, on the suggestion of Antony which was not opposed by Octavianus, put in the list of those doomed to immediate destruction. Soldiers were imme- diately sent in pursuit, and although his attendants wished . to offer opposition, Cicero forbade them. and surrendered to his pursuers‚ by whom he was immediately killed.
